    slug: "understanding-analytics-dashboard",
    excerpt: "A guide to the Analytics section — what data sources it draws from, what each chart represents, and how to use the dashboard to monitor and improve your marketing performance.",
    content: `<h2>Analytics Data Sources</h2><p>The Analytics dashboard aggregates data from multiple sources: your connected Google Search Console (organic search performance), our platform's rank tracking (keyword position history), the backlink module (link acquisition trends), the campaigns module (email and social performance), and the leads module (lead generation and funnel metrics). When Google Search Console is not connected, some organic traffic metrics will be limited or unavailable.</p><h2>Traffic and Search Performance Charts</h2><p>The Organic Search chart shows clicks and impressions from Google over the selected time period. The search performance trend reveals whether your organic visibility is growing, stable, or declining — a critical leading indicator of SEO program health. The Keyword Distribution chart shows how your tracked keywords are distributed across ranking positions (1–3, 4–10, 11–20, 20+). Growth in the 1–3 bucket indicates your top-priority keywords are winning high-visibility positions.</p><h2>Lead Generation Funnel</h2><p>The Funnel chart visualizes your lead pipeline: total leads by status (New → Contacted → Qualified → Converted). The conversion rate between each funnel stage reveals where your lead nurturing is most effective and where leads drop off. A low New-to-Contacted rate suggests your sales or marketing follow-up process needs improvement. A low Qualified-to-Converted rate may indicate a pricing, product, or sales process issue worth investigating with your sales team.</p>`,
