    slug: "lead-conversion-revenue-analytics",
    excerpt: "Track your leads through the full conversion funnel — from first touch to closed deal — and attribute revenue to specific marketing channels, campaigns, and content pieces.",
    content: `<h2>Lead Status and Funnel Tracking</h2><p>Lead statuses in the platform map to your sales funnel stages: New → Contacted → Qualified → Converted (or Lost). Move leads through statuses manually as their funnel stage progresses, or configure automated status updates triggered by email engagement events (a lead clicking a pricing link might automatically progress to "Qualified"). The Funnel report shows aggregate counts at each stage and calculates conversion rates between stages.</p><h2>Revenue Attribution</h2><p>For leads that convert to customers, record the deal value in the lead's Revenue field. This enables revenue attribution reporting: which campaigns, content pieces, and traffic sources drove the most revenue — not just the most leads. A lead source that generates 100 leads at $1,000 average deal value ($100K revenue) is more valuable than a source generating 200 leads at $300 average deal value ($60K revenue), even though it generates fewer total leads. Revenue-weighted attribution reveals true marketing ROI rather than misleading lead-volume metrics.</p><h2>Channel Attribution Reports</h2><p>The Channel Attribution report shows leads and revenue attributed to each traffic source (organic search, email campaigns, social media, direct traffic, referral). This report requires UTM parameter tracking on your marketing links to work accurately — ensure all links in your email campaigns, social posts, and paid campaigns include UTM parameters so the platform can attribute leads to the correct channel and campaign. Configure UTM templates in Settings → UTM Builder for consistent tracking across your marketing team.</p>`,
